# Sparse Vectors & N-grams - ENGLISH CORRECTED NOTES

**SPARSE VECTORS**
BoW vectors are sparse vectors (mostly 0s). Real vocab = thousands/lakhs words, but docs use few words.
- **Memory waste**: Most space stores zeros
- **Computation slow**

**N-GRAMS**
Single words (unigrams) miss context. N-grams capture consecutive word groups:
| Type     | N  | Example: "I love deep learning"              |
|----------|----|---------------------------------------------|
| Unigram  | 1  | ["I", "love", "deep", "learning"]           |
| Bigram   | 2  | ["I love", "love deep", "deep learning"]    |
| Trigram  | 3  | ["I love deep", "love deep learning"]       |

**Details:**
- **Unigrams (N=1)**: Individual words - most basic
- **Bigrams (N=2)**: 2 consecutive words (captures "not good" vs "good")
- **Trigrams (N=3)**: 3 words - more context, vocab explodes

# BoW Limitations

| Limitation          | Problem                          |
|---------------------|----------------------------------|
| **No word order**   | "dog bites man" = "man bites dog" |
| **No semantics**    | "apple" (fruit) = "apple" (company) |
| **High dimensionality** | 100K vocab = 100K features/doc |
| **No context**      | "not good" = "good"             |
| **Common words dominate** | "the", "is" → highest scores |











